Although in general, it is more convenient/required to work with functors of groupoids instead of sets. This is true for moduli of curves.

===Technical remarks about infinitesimals===
Infinitesimals have long been in use by mathematicians for non-rigorous arguments in calculus. The idea is that if we consider polynomials formula_48 with an infinitesimal formula_49, then only the first order terms really matter; that is, we can consider
:formula_50
A simple application of this is that we can find the derivatives of monomials using infinitesimals:
:formula_51
the formula_49 term contains the derivative of the monomial, demonstrating its use in calculus. We could also interpret this equation as the first two terms of the Taylor expansion of the monomial. Infinitesimals can be made rigorous using nilpotent elements in local artin algebras. In the ring formula_53 we see that arguments with infinitesimals can work. This motivates the notation formula_54, which is called the ring of dual numbers. 

Moreover, if we want to consider higher-order terms of a Taylor approximation then we could consider the artin algebras formula_55. For our monomial, suppose we want to write out the second order expansion, then
:formula_56
Recall that a Taylor expansion (at zero) can be written out as
:formula_57
hence the previous two equations show that the second derivative of formula_58 is formula_59.

In general, since we want to consider arbitrary order Taylor expansions in any number of variables, we will consider the category of all local artin algebras over a field.

